<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-07-31T18:10:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-04-14T18:11:00-05:00" n="764" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d764">
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Municipal Council of Salza Irpina</hi>.</head>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Salza Irpina</placeName>, <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-volume-rules" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1865-07-31T23:59:59+00:49" notBefore="1865-04-15T00:00:00+00:49">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <note rend="inline" rendition="#center" type="source">[Translation.]</note>
                    <p>The entire municipality of Salza Irpina, full of horror for the assassination
                        consummated upon the person of the illustrious President, Abraham Lincoln,
                        deliberated unanimously to express their sentiments of grief for that
                        horrible event; also, of the sentiment of sympathy which this population
                        feel for the people of America, and for the sacred cause courageously fought
                        for by the martyrs who are now pitied by all Europe; and the municipality
                        begs the mayor to send a copy of this act to the American consul at
                        Naples.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <list>
                                <item>CAVALIERE MICHELE CAPOZZI, <hi rend="italic">Mayor</hi>.</item>
                                <item>FELICIANO PASQUALE, <hi rend="italic">Assessor</hi>.</item>
                                <item>CARMINE DE PAISOLE, <hi rend="italic">Secretary</hi>.</item>
                            </list>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>